{"id":"2202.11014","submitter":"Howard Heaton","authors":"Howard Heaton, Samy Wu Fung, Stanley Osher","title":"Global Solutions to Nonconvex Problems by Evolution of Hamilton-Jacobi\n  PDEs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Computing tasks may often be posed as optimization problems. The objective\nfunctions for real-world scenarios are often nonconvex and/or\nnondifferentiable. State-of-the-art methods for solving these problems\ntypically only guarantee convergence to local minima. This work presents\nHamilton-Jacobi-based Moreau Adaptive Descent (HJ-MAD), a zero-order algorithm\nwith guaranteed convergence to global minima, assuming continuity of the\nobjective function. The core idea is to compute gradients of the Moreau\nenvelope of the objective (which is \"piece-wise convex\") with adaptive\nsmoothing parameters. Gradients of the Moreau envelope \\rev{(\\ie proximal\noperators)} are approximated via the Hopf-Lax formula for the viscous\nHamilton-Jacobi equation. Our numerical examples illustrate global convergence.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Feb 2022 16:33:28 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 9 Oct 2022 14:23:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-11"}
