s were measured from our grid of\nmodels to determine the effect of each physical parameter on the observed SN II\ndiversity. We argue that explosion energy is the physical parameter causing the\ngreatest impact on SN II diversity, when assuming standard single-star\nevolution as in the models used in this study. The inclusion of pre-SN models\nassuming higher mass loss produces a significant increase in the strength of\nsome correlations, particularly those between the progenitor hydrogen-rich\nenvelope mass and the plateau and optically thick phase durations. These\ndifferences clearly show the impact of having different treatments of stellar\nevolution, implying that changes in the assumption of standard single-star\nevolution are necessary for a complete understanding of SN II diversity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 22 Feb 2022 22:34:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-20"}
